  "answer": "The most beneficial conservation actions for establishing new populations of threatened toad species in the UK are:\n\n1. **Translocate natterjack toads** (Action ID 859): Rated as 'Likely to be beneficial', this action has established breeding populations in 30\u201370% of cases, particularly on dune or saltmarsh habitats. Success rates improve with replicated translocations of wild (vs. captive-bred) toads and habitat management.\n\n2. **Create ponds for natterjack toads** (Action ID 866): Rated as 'Beneficial', pond creation (combined with other interventions) significantly increased populations in multiple studies. Created ponds reduced tadpole mortality from drying but required management to address predation risks.\n\nThese actions focus on habitat restoration and strategic translocation, prioritizing natural habitat types and wild-sourced individuals for higher success rates.",
